    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Royal Gardens Kew</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Oct 7/79</date>
                    <salute>Dear Darwin</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Please get me <hi rend="underline">good</hi> specimens of enclosed from Miss Wedgwood Garden<ref target="#foot.f1"/>   I want to draw it, &amp; also roots (if perennial:)</p>
<p>In haste | Yrs | J D Hooker</p>
<p><hi rend="underline">Saracenia</hi> &amp; <hi rend="underline">Darlingtonia</hi> do not care for “light &amp; sweetness” hitherto<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1218.xml">Emma Darwin’s</ref> sister, <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5039.xml">Elizabeth Wedgwood,</ref> lived in Down. The enclosure has not been found.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><hi rend="italic">Sarracenia</hi> (trumpet pitcher-plants) and <hi rend="italic">Darlingtonia californica</hi> (the California pitcher-plant; <hi rend="italic">Darlingtonia</hi> is a monospecific genus) are insectivorous plants. Hooker had evidently found that they were not heliotropic (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12242.xml">letter from J. D. Hooker, 2 October 1879 and n. 4</ref>). ‘Light &amp; sweetness’: an ironic reference to the idiom ‘sweetness and light’, popularised by <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_154.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Matthew Arnold’s</ref> <hi rend="italic">Culture and anarchy</hi> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_9742.xml">Arnold 1869</ref>).</note>
        </div>
    
